 -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat role do material objects play in the in-situ, embodied and spatial circumstances of interaction? How do people organize their embodied conduct with regard to such objects, and how is this consequential in and for their work practices? In this volume, contributors focus on these questions in terms of connections between ongoing courses of interaction within work practices, object materiality and mobility in space, bodily movement and manipulation of objects, and language. The chapters in this book address a broad range of settings and actions (including dressmaking, foreign language teaching, international business meetings and forklift driving) where a variety of objects become relevant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBody languagevCase studies. 0aNonverbal communicationvCase studies. 0aPsycholinguisticsvCase studies. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Workplace Culture.2bisacsh  aSocial interaction.  aWorkplace practices.  abodies in the workplace.  aembodied action.  amateriality in space and time.  amateriality.1 aDay, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, Dennis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Stefani, Elwys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFele, Giolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHazel, Spencer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinemann, Trine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorlacher, Anne-Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonzoni, C